Cleaning carboys is a real pain. Soaking for days isn't an option and
filling w/ cleaner is wasteful. I might break down and start heating a
gallon of water on my stove and shaking the carboy w/ caustic cleaner.
That's kind of dangerous, however.

The hardest spot is the dried krausen ring.  One idea I had was to fill
w/ a couple gallons of cleaner, cork it w/ a solid stopper and place it
over a PVC pipe and let it soak. That would save quite a bit of water
and cleaner.

So far, the best method I came up with is:

- Rinse the carboy w/ a jet bottle washer
- Fill carboy w/ hot water, add cleaner, then use a wine degaser on a
drill and get a good vortex going.
- Let it sit for an hour or so, then drain w/ a siphon
- Rinse well
- Acid Rinse
- Inspect w/ a flash light for any film

This is the reason I like buckets, but right now I'm trying to lock
down my beer's bacteria load and want to use glass.
